cuems-power-bridge (0.3.0-2) UNRELEASED; urgency=medium

  * shelly-mjs: add a cancellable grace window. After SW0 -> OFF the script
    waits CANCEL_GRACE_S seconds (default 5, set via
    `cuems-power-bridge-install-mjs --cancel-grace N`) before POSTing
    /shutdown; flipping SW0 back ON within the window cancels it, so an
    accidental/changed-mind flip never reaches the bridge. Requires SW0 in
    detached mode (already required by the arm-timer design). The grace/cancel
    applies to the physical switch only -- a Companion/direct POST /shutdown is
    committed immediately (documented). Code-review hardening: the mJS logs and
    skips a redundant OFF while a POST is in flight (no silent swallow); the
    installer's literal patching is table-driven with a uniform pre-replace
    guard for BRIDGE/TOKEN/CANCEL_GRACE_S (TOKEN was previously unguarded) and
    the grace default is single-sourced; README updated; unit tests added for
    the patching logic.
  * Add modular projector/display power control. New `displays/` subpackage:
    a `DisplayDriver` abstraction with a per-protocol registry, plus a
    `PJLinkDriver` (PJLink over TCP 4352) — covers the Epson EB-690SU /
    EB-815E and most other PJLink projectors. `DisplayManager` fans
    power on/off/status across the configured fleet concurrently, with
    per-device error isolation.
  * Lifecycle integration: projectors power ON when the engine reports a
    project loaded (engine-status listener, edge-detected) and OFF as part
    of the orderly /shutdown sequence. Projector failures are logged and
    never abort or delay the safety-critical shutdown.
  * Config: new globals `projector_power_on_on_load`,
    `projector_power_off_on_shutdown`, `projector_command_timeout_s`, and
    per-device `projector.N.{host,driver,name,port,password}` keys.
  * New diagnostic CLI `cuems-power-bridge-test-projector <host>
    {status|on|off}` for bring-up (with /usr/bin shim).
  * /status payload gains a `projectors` array (cached snapshot, no live
    network call). Unit tests for PJLink framing/auth/CRLF/ERR3, config
    parsing, and manager fan-out isolation.
  * Operator note: a projector needs "Standby Mode Communications = ON"
    (network standby) + PJLink enabled for power-ON from a fully-off state.
  * Hardening (code review): cancel an in-flight power-on before powering
    off so POWR 1 can't race POWR 0 during shutdown; run the shutdown
    power-off concurrently with the node reachability poll, bounded so a
    hung projector can't stall shutdown; PJLink ERR3-to-exhaustion now
    raises DisplayUnconfirmed so /status reports UNKNOWN (not a false
    "off"); re-arm projector power-on across an engine reconnect;
    projector_command_timeout_s accepts fractional seconds; per-device
    state is index-aligned (duplicate display labels no longer collapse);
    /status key renamed `projectors` -> `displays`.

  * shutdown SSH: connect to nodes as cuems-admin (the new default ssh_user)
    instead of the nologin cuems service user, so the unattended
    `sudo /sbin/poweroff` can exec. deploy_keys.py rewritten: connects AS
    ssh_user and writes that user's own ~/.ssh/authorized_keys (no sudo, so no
    password hang), locking the bridge key with
    `restrict,command="sudo /sbin/poweroff"`. Idempotent (replaces any prior
    entry for the key). Pairs with cuems-common 99-cuems-admin-poweroff.
  * shelly-mjs: send the auth header via HTTP.Request, not HTTP.POST. Shelly's
    HTTP.POST silently drops a custom headers map (it only honors
    content_type), so X-Auth-Token never reached the bridge and every
    /shutdown got 401 bad_token. HTTP.Request transmits arbitrary headers.
  * shelly-mjs: on SW0 -> ON with no shutdown pending, re-close the relay
    (Switch.Set on:true) to restore mains -- the "relay on -> machines boot"
    production path (needs SW0 detached + BIOS power-on-after-AC-loss = ON).
  * bridge: only append --no-block to the local controller poweroff for
    systemctl commands. The default sudo /sbin/poweroff is the systemctl
    poweroff applet, which rejects --no-block (unrecognized option) and so
    silently no-op'd the controller shutdown (nodes were unaffected).
  * auto-load: harden boot-time auto-load against slow/late nodes (WoL
    recovery, fsck). Previously the bridge fired project_ready ~2 s after
    the controller booted -- before the nodes' engines had joined the NNG
    bus -- so the engine froze its required-node set with those nodes
    EXCLUDED and GO stayed blocked until a manual engine restart. The fix
    is entirely bridge-side (no engine/editor/frontend change):
    - Wait for the expected node-engines to connect to the controller's
      NNG hub before loading. node-engines are NNG Bus0 clients of the hub,
      so the bridge reads its own ESTABLISHED socket table via `ss` (no
      root) and gates on "expected node IPs connected to <nng_hub_port>" --
      exactly the engine's own liveness criterion, so exclusion is
      prevented at the source. New module `cluster_bus.py`.
    - Require armed==yes (not merely project_loaded) before declaring
      success, with soft retries; a never-arming load self-heals on a 30 s
      cadence instead of giving up.
    - New `engine_state.fully_ready()` (loaded AND armed); new
      `network_map.slave_ips()` (trusts <ip> for bus-matching, degrades
      gracefully on missing/stale <ip> via a count-based fallback).
    - nng_hub_port is read from <nng_hub_port> in settings.xml (single
      source of truth), never a separate conf knob.
    - New config: auto_load_wait_nodes, auto_load_node_ids (CSV subset),
      auto_load_node_timeout_s, auto_load_node_settle_s,
      auto_load_armed_timeout_s, auto_load_max_attempts.
    - /status gains `autoload_pending` (role_ids still off the bus,
      distinct from shutdown's `nodes_pending`) and `auto_load_armed`.
    - Re-drive guard: if an operator loads a DIFFERENT project while the
      bridge is waiting/retrying, it backs off rather than clobbering it.
    - stop() cancels the (now long-running) auto-load task before engine/
      editor teardown so /shutdown stays prompt even mid bus-wait.
    - Projector power-on is debounced so an auto-load re-drive's transient
      load empty->non-empty flip doesn't re-power displays repeatedly.
    - Hardening (code review): record the driven project's unix_name as soon
      as it loads (not only on arm) so the re-drive guard catches an operator
      loading a different project DURING the pre-arm soft-retry window; reset
      the projector debounce on engine disconnect so a reconnect within the
      window still re-asserts power; make the editor-error watcher
      exception-safe and wrap each auto-load attempt so no stray exception can
      kill the loop (it self-heals on the next tick); mtime-cache the
      network_map.xml parse so retries don't re-read it (an operator edit
      mid-recovery still bumps mtime -> reparse).
  * Packaging: strip `websockets` (shipped by cuems-utils into the shared
    /usr/lib/cuems venv) from the bundled deps so `dpkg -i` no longer aborts
    with a file-overwrite conflict against cuems-utils; rely on cuems-utils'
    copy (it is a hard dependency). Also `export PYTHONNOUSERSITE=1` in
    debian/rules so the build venv's pip ignores the builder's ~/.local -- a
    dep already present there (e.g. typing_extensions from a stray
    `pip install --user`) was treated as satisfied and omitted from the .deb,
    crashing at runtime with ModuleNotFoundError. Both latent in 0.3.0-1,
    surfaced on a clean rebuild.

